OK.

20:29.000 --> 20:33.480
The avatar, I mean, unless for you,

20:33.480 --> 20:37.360
romance, love, and companionship means sitting in a room

20:37.360 --> 20:41.240
and imagining people, which I think for 99 to 100% of people,

20:41.240 --> 20:42.480
that's not the case.

20:42.480 --> 20:44.760
Ultimately, it's about meeting someone.

20:44.760 --> 20:49.160
So the way I think of it is that in a way,

20:49.160 --> 20:51.880
the technology is just a discovery tool.

20:51.880 --> 20:54.840
And I think the goal for most people

20:54.840 --> 20:58.600
should be to get offline as soon as possible.

20:58.600 --> 21:02.200
No, you're not spotting them across the room,

21:02.200 --> 21:03.960
or you're not spotting them in a class,

21:03.960 --> 21:06.000
or on the subway, or in a bar, or whatever.

21:06.000 --> 21:08.360
I think for some people that feels very strange,

21:08.360 --> 21:11.400
because we've become so used to that way of meeting.

21:11.400 --> 21:13.280
But it's really, it's just a discovery tool.

21:13.280 --> 21:18.480
And so I don't think the profile matters as much.

21:18.480 --> 21:21.120
I think the profile is one of those things of an online dating

21:21.120 --> 21:23.160
that is sort of a superficial difference.

21:23.160 --> 21:26.880
It's a fun thing to focus on because it can be funny.

21:26.880 --> 21:32.720
And it can be the source of sort of a lot of fibbing

21:32.720 --> 21:33.560
about yourself.

21:33.560 --> 21:35.520
But ultimately, you're going to put that aside,

21:35.520 --> 21:36.600
and you've got to go out.

21:36.600 --> 21:40.200
I think it's interesting that if you way, way before any

21:40.200 --> 21:42.040
of this could have taken place, one of the things

21:42.040 --> 21:46.360
that both of you are describing as sort of the idealization,

21:46.360 --> 21:48.160
that you idealize yourself, and you

21:48.160 --> 21:50.760
idealize the person with whom you're communicating

21:50.760 --> 21:53.640
on with online dating until you can no longer do that,

21:53.640 --> 21:56.280
because you're confronted with the actual person

21:56.280 --> 21:57.880
and have to relate to them.

21:57.880 --> 22:00.960
But this actually, at a completely different scale,

22:00.960 --> 22:05.040
is of course the basis of much of Renaissance ideas

22:05.040 --> 22:09.280
about love and embedded in poetry and so on,

22:09.280 --> 22:14.440
that in fact it's best not to meet that ideal love.

22:14.440 --> 22:17.360
And many of the poets never did meet that ideal love.

22:17.360 --> 22:20.520
They saw them in church and invented an entire thing

22:20.520 --> 22:24.240
about who they were and how great they

22:24.240 --> 22:28.240
and how they epitomized all of these ideals.

22:28.240 --> 22:32.600
But when they met them, it would be a completely different thing.

22:32.600 --> 22:36.120
And in fact, when they met them, they usually were very happy

22:36.120 --> 22:39.440
that those great ideals were married to someone completely

22:39.440 --> 22:41.040
different, and they didn't have to deal with them

22:41.040 --> 22:42.640
on a day-to-day basis.

22:42.640 --> 22:45.920
But it is, in a way, it's the same kind of thing

22:45.920 --> 22:48.520
that you overlay on somebody.

22:48.520 --> 22:54.200
It seems to me what you said that you studied romantic love.

22:54.200 --> 22:58.840
But from what I hear, first there seems to be the issue

22:58.840 --> 23:03.320
of interest, whether it's on the internet or in person

23:03.320 --> 23:05.600
or whatever there has to be interest.

23:05.600 --> 23:07.560
Then there is a term you didn't use,

23:07.560 --> 23:10.800
and I wonder why you chose not to use it,

23:10.800 --> 23:12.720
which is infatuation.

23:12.720 --> 23:16.040
And then you came to romantic love,

23:16.040 --> 23:20.720
which different people have different definitions of.

23:20.720 --> 23:23.840
So I thought maybe.

23:23.840 --> 23:27.360
So for my definition I like comes from Lane Hatfield

23:27.360 --> 23:30.640
for romantic love, and it's the intense desire

23:30.640 --> 23:34.840
for emotional union with another person.

23:34.840 --> 23:35.880
Unity, did you say?

23:35.880 --> 23:37.480
Emotional union.

23:37.480 --> 23:38.480
Union.

23:38.480 --> 23:39.440
With another person.

23:39.440 --> 23:42.480
That intense desire for emotional union.

23:42.480 --> 23:46.560
That is how romance can begin.

23:46.560 --> 23:49.520
And certainly what I'm talking about,

23:49.520 --> 23:51.240
you could use the word infatuation.

23:51.240 --> 23:53.040
It can start out that way.

23:53.040 --> 23:56.560
Where one of the things that we asked people

23:56.560 --> 23:59.320
who we were interviewing to become subjects

23:59.320 --> 24:01.920
in the experiment, the most important question,

24:01.920 --> 24:06.800
was what percentage of the day do you think about this person?

24:06.800 --> 24:09.120
